  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Master the Temperature Differential</strong> - Serve Bordeaux at 65-68°F to showcase its structured tannins and cedar-cassis complexity, while Burgundy performs best at 60-63°F to preserve its delicate red fruit aromatics and silky texture. The warmer temperature helps Bordeaux's Cabernet Sauvignon backbone integrate, but would overwhelm Burgundy's ethereal Pinot Noir character.</li>

  <li><strong>Read the Vintage Codes</strong> - In Bordeaux, focus on Right Bank vintages (2009, 2010, 2016) for Merlot-dominant wines that drink earlier, versus Left Bank years (2005, 2010, 2016, 2019) for Cabernet Sauvignon-based wines needing more time. For Burgundy, seek cooler vintages like 2014, 2016, and 2019 for elegant, age-worthy wines, while warmer years like 2015 and 2020 offer approachable, fruit-forward styles.</li>

  <li><strong>Decode the Decanting Strategy</strong> - Young Bordeaux (under 10 years) benefits from 2-3 hours of aggressive decanting to soften tannins and integrate oak, while mature Bordeaux (15+ years) needs just 30-60 minutes to preserve delicate secondary aromas. Burgundy rarely needs decanting—young wines require only 15-30 minutes to open aromatics, and older bottles should be served directly from bottle to avoid losing precious perfume.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Your Glass Architecture</strong> - Use a larger Bordeaux glass with a tall bowl to concentrate the wine's powerful structure and allow tannins to soften through aeration. Burgundy demands a balloon-shaped Burgundy glass with a wider bowl to capture and concentrate the wine's fleeting aromatics—the broader surface area helps release Pinot Noir's complex secondary and tertiary notes.</li>

  <li><strong>Navigate the Aging Sweet Spots</strong> - Bordeaux's tannic structure means most wines hit their stride between 8-15 years, with top châteaux improving for 20-30 years. Burgundy's delicate structure means village wines peak at 5-10 years, while Grand Crus can evolve beautifully for 15-25 years, but they're often delicious young due to Pinot Noir's immediate charm versus Cabernet Sauvignon's need for integration time.</li>

  <li><strong>Understand Terroir Expression Windows</strong> - Bordeaux shows its terroir through structure and minerality that emerges after 7-10 years when tannins settle—Left Bank wines reveal pencil lead and graphite, Right Bank shows clay-driven richness. Burgundy expresses terroir immediately through aromatics and texture—limestone soils create mineral tension, clay brings richness, and these characteristics are apparent even in young wines.</li>

  <li><strong>Master Food Pairing Timing</strong> - Young Bordeaux pairs with robust preparations (grilled ribeye, aged cheeses) because high tannins need fat and protein to soften, while mature Bordeaux complements elegant dishes (duck breast, mushroom risotto) as tannins have integrated. Burgundy's higher acidity and lower tannins make it versatile—pair young wines with roasted chicken or salmon, mature wines with game birds or truffle dishes.</li>

  <li><strong>Recognize Value Timing Cycles</strong> - Buy Bordeaux during the primeur campaign (18 months after harvest) for best prices on top estates, then cellar for 8-15 years. For Burgundy, purchase upon release or shortly after, as prices tend to rise quickly due to limited production—village wines offer immediate drinking pleasure, while Premier and Grand Crus reward 3-5 years of cellaring for optimal complexity.</li>
</ol>



  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which is better for wine beginners - Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bordeaux is generally more beginner-friendly due to its consistent blending style and clearer regional hierarchy. The tannin structure in Bordeaux provides a familiar "red wine" profile, while Burgundy's single-varietal approach and subtle terroir differences require more developed palate experience. Start with a Bordeaux Supérieur or Côtes de Bordeaux before progressing to Burgundy's nuanced Pinot Noirs.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the main difference between Bordeaux and Burgundy grape varieties?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Bordeaux relies on blends, primarily Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot for reds, with Cabernet Franc, Petit Verdot, and Malbec as supporting varieties. Burgundy is built on single varietals - Pinot Noir for reds and Chardonnay for whites - which express pure terroir without the complexity of blending. This fundamental difference creates Bordeaux's structured, layered profiles versus Burgundy's transparent, site-specific expressions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should Bordeaux and Burgundy be served at different temperatures?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes - Bordeaux's tannin structure benefits from slightly warmer serving temperatures (60-65°F) to soften the mouthfeel and reveal complexity. Burgundy Pinot Noir should be served cooler (55-60°F) to preserve its delicate aromatics and prevent alcohol dominance. Both regions' white wines perform best at 50-55°F, though white Burgundy can handle slightly warmer temperatures due to its fuller body and oak integration.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why is Burgundy more expensive than Bordeaux?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Burgundy's higher prices stem from drastically smaller production - the entire Burgundy region produces less wine annually than Château Margaux alone. The fragmented ownership system creates tiny vineyard plots (some less than an acre), while Pinot Noir's difficulty to cultivate and vintage sensitivity add production costs. Bordeaux's estate system allows for larger-scale production and more consistent pricing across quality levels.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which ages better - Bordeaux or Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Top-level Bordeaux generally has superior aging potential, with classified growths developing for 20-50+ years due to Cabernet Sauvignon's tannin structure and acidity. Burgundy's aging is more variable - Grand Cru sites can evolve beautifully for 15-30 years, but Pinot Noir's delicate nature makes it more vintage-dependent. However, aged Burgundy often provides more complex aromatics, while aged Bordeaux offers greater structural evolution.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good Bordeaux vs Burgundy alternative for similar taste profiles?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For Bordeaux-style wines, explore Cabernet-Merlot blends from Washington State's Columbia Valley or Australia's Margaret River, which offer similar structure at lower prices. Burgundy alternatives include Oregon Pinot Noir from Willamette Valley, which shares cool-climate elegance, or Gevrey-Chambertin-style wines from Germany's Ahr Valley. These regions capture the essential character profiles while offering better value propositions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake when choosing between Bordeaux and Burgundy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is expecting Bordeaux power from Burgundy or Burgundy elegance from Bordeaux - they're fundamentally different wine styles. Many people also choose based on reputation rather than personal preference, buying expensive Burgundy when they actually prefer Bordeaux's structure, or vice versa. Always taste both styles before investing in higher-tier bottles to understand which profile suits your palate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you pair Bordeaux and Burgundy with the same foods?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While both pair with red meat, they excel with different preparations - Bordeaux's tannins complement grilled steaks, lamb, and aged cheeses, while Burgundy's elegance suits roasted poultry, mushroom dishes, and lighter game. Bordeaux handles bold, sauce-heavy dishes better due to its structure, whereas Burgundy shines with subtle, earth-driven flavors that won't overpower its delicate fruit profile. The key is matching the wine's intensity to the dish's richness.</p>
